ALSO mirror tty_askname's backspace handler into the NOMUX shadow buffer.

The backspace handler in tty_askname() (NetHack's name-prompt loop)
emits the standard \b/space/\b erase sequence directly via
putchar(). Those raw control characters bypass nomux_putch (which
ignores ch < 32), so the shadow buffer is left with the pre-erase
character in place AND ttyDisplay->curx isn't decremented on UNIX.
The next typed character lands one column past where the user
expects it, and the misalignment persists for the rest of the prompt.

Without this fix, recording a session that types its name at
chargen (e.g. "touriss<BS>to<ENTER>") shows "tourisst" / "tourissto"
in the captured screens even though the in-game name buffer
correctly reads "touristo".

diff -urN -x *.bak a/win/tty/wintty.c b/win/tty/wintty.c
--- a/win/tty/wintty.c
+++ b/win/tty/wintty.c
@@ -716,6 +716,25 @@
                     (void) putchar('\b');
                     (void) putchar(' ');
                     (void) putchar('\b');
 #endif
+#ifdef NOMUX_CAPTURE
+                    /* Mirror the visible erase into the NOMUX shadow
+                     * buffer. The \b/space/\b sequence emitted above
+                     * via putchar() bypasses nomux_putch (which
+                     * ignores ch < 32). On UNIX, ttyDisplay->curx
+                     * wasn't touched by the bare putchar() calls; on
+                     * WIN32CON it was already decremented above.
+                     * After this block, curx points at the erased
+                     * column and the shadow buffer cell at that
+                     * column holds a space — mirroring the real
+                     * terminal. Without this, screen captures show
+                     * the pre-erase char and subsequent typed chars
+                     * land at the wrong column for the rest of the
+                     * prompt. */
+#ifndef WIN32CON
+                    if (ttyDisplay->curx > 0)
+                        ttyDisplay->curx--;
+#endif
+                    nomux_putch(' ');
+#endif
                 }
                 continue;
             }
